qas.question: Which specific type of wood within ring-porous woods have more fibers to make it strong?
When there is less latewood, what is diminishing?
Does slow or rapid growth make relatively porous, light wood?
What kind of oak has just 6-10% volume of large vessels in the log?
What kind of fibers are in the latewood of good oak, making it very firm?

context: In ring-porous woods of good growth it is usually the <a0_0>latewood<a0_0/> in which the thick-walled, strength-giving fibers are most abundant. As the <a1_0>breadth of ring<a1_0/> diminishes, this latewood is reduced so that very <a2_0>slow<a2_0/> growth produces comparatively light, porous wood composed of thin-walled vessels and wood parenchyma. In <a3_0>good<a3_0/> oak these large vessels of the earlywood occupy from 6 to 10 percent of the volume of the log, while in inferior material they may make up 25% or more. The latewood of good oak is dark colored and firm, and consists mostly of <a4_0>thick-walled<a4_0/> fibers which form one-half or more of the wood. In inferior oak, this latewood is much reduced both in quantity and quality. Such variation is very largely the result of rate of growth.
